{{italic title}}
'''''Live like Ali, die like Hussein''''' is a religious slogan used by [[Shia Muslims]],<ref name="Manger2013">{{cite book|author=Leif Manger|title=Muslim Diversity: Local Islam in Global Contexts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8WGOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA21|date=18 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-81857-8|pages=21–}}</ref><ref name="Jafrī2003">{{cite book|author=Maqsood Jafrī|title=The gleams of wisdom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nsQLAQAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Sigma Press}}</ref> referring to the martyrs [[Ali]] and his son [[Husayn ibn Ali]].

==Other famous Shia slogans==
*'''There is no hero''' (some versions replace ''hero'' with ''man'')<ref>{{cite book|author1=Yasser Tabbaa|author2=Sabrina Mervin|title=Najaf, the Gate of wisdom|date=2014|publisher=UNESCO|isbn=9789231000287|page=23}}</ref> '''except Ali; there is no sword except [[Zulfiqar]]''' - [[Zulfiqar#Invocation and depiction|This slogan]] is very famous among Shia;<ref>{{cite book|author1=Vali Nasr|title=The Shia Revival: How Conflicts within Islam Will Shape the Future|date=17 Apr 2007|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=9780393066401|page=37}}</ref> reported to have originated from Muhammad and is widely engraved on weapons,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Madonna Gauding|title=The Signs and Symbols Bible: The Definitive Guide to Mysterious Markings|date=1 Oct 2009|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=9781402770043|page=105}}</ref> such as swords. The slogan is frequently preceded by a Shia invocation to Ali<ref>{{cite book|author1=Syed Akbar Hyder|title=Reliving Karbala : Martyrdom in South Asian Memory|date=23 Mar 2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195345933|pages=120–1}}</ref> and is also “central to the [[dua|du’a]] (prayer) of [[Ismaili|Isma’ilis]], who recite it in one breath together with their declaration of faith in God.”<ref>{{cite book|author1=Gülru Necipoğlu|author2=Karen A. Leal|title=Muqarnas|date=1 Oct 2009|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004175891|page=81}}</ref>
*'''Every place is [[Karbala]]; every day is [[Day of Ashura|Ashura]]'''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Jacob N. Kinnard|title=Places in Motion: The Fluid Identities of Temples, Images, and Pilgrims|date=26 Jun 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199359660|page=165}}</ref> - This slogan is often repeated by Shia.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Juan Eduardo Campo|title=Encyclopedia of Islam|date=1 Jan 2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438126968|page=423}}</ref> It is attributed to a [[hadith]] of the 12th Imam, [[Muhammad al-Mahdi]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Henry Munson|title=Islam and Revolution in the Middle East|date=1 Sep 1989|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300046045|page=23}}</ref>

